data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — work identically in .NET 8, so **no migration is needed** for Thread.Abort concerns.

That said, for a .NET 8 modernization, consider replacing raw threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll` for cleaner parallelism:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you need it later — which is the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`.
